---
rules:
  - name: 'React Component Structure'
    description: 'Guidelines for React component organization'
    files: '**/components/**/*.{tsx,jsx}'
    instructions: |
      - Use functional components with TypeScript
      - Props interface should be named [ComponentName]Props
      - Keep components focused and single-responsibility
      - Extract complex logic into custom hooks
      - Use proper React imports (no * imports)
      - Implement error boundaries where appropriate
      - Use React.memo() for performance optimization when needed
      - Follow component directory structure:
        - index.tsx: Main component
        - types.ts: Component types
        - utils.ts: Helper functions
        - style.ts: Styled components
        - hooks.ts: Component-specific hooks
      - Handle component-level errors appropriately
      - Ensure accessibility compliance (ARIA labels, roles)
      - Use Storybook for component development
      - Implement responsive design patterns
      - Handle both touch and mouse input appropriately
      - Follow layout patterns:
        - Support 'default', 'classic', and 'stacked' layouts
        - Handle proper layout transitions
        - Use proper sizing and positioning
        - Support proper iPad layout modes
      - Follow UI component patterns:
        - Use FloatingPanel for floating UIs
        - Use proper menu structures
        - Implement proper drag and drop
        - Handle proper z-indexing
        - Use proper animation patterns
      - Follow state management patterns:
        - Use proper context providers
        - Handle proper state updates
        - Implement proper error recovery
        - Use proper loading states
      - Follow event handling patterns:
        - Use proper event delegation
        - Handle proper cleanup
        - Use proper event bubbling
        - Implement proper keyboard shortcuts
      - Component performance optimization:
        - Memoize expensive calculations with useMemo
        - Memoize callback functions with useCallback
        - Use React.memo for pure components
        - Avoid unnecessary re-renders
        - Use virtualization for long lists
      - Component testing:
        - Write unit tests for components
        - Test component behavior
        - Test component interactions
        - Test edge cases
        - Test accessibility
